{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492547"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1095"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1095"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.67,0.1,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31819"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1792"},{"type":"tags","id":"4645"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42218"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a five-day history of painful sores on the lips. He reports a painful tingling and burning sensation. He has a past history of similar episodes that used to self-resolve within one to two weeks. He has multiple female sexual partners but reports that he consistently uses condoms. He has a medical history of systemic lupus erythematosus. His medications include glucocorticoids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Inspection reveals multiple vesicopustular lesions which are grouped predominantly over the right side of the mouth on the cutaneous and mucosal lip along the vermilion border, and extending to the left side of the mouth (Image). Examination of the oral mucosa is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Impetigo","Herpes simplex infection","Herpes zoster infection","Aphthous stomatitis","Bullous systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of oral herpes or herpes labialis and is caused by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eherpes simplex\u003C/strong\u003E virus type 1 (HSV-1). The infection spreads through oral-oral or genital-oral contact with someone who already has HSV-1 disease and is currently shedding the virus. Primary infection with HSV-1 presents with gingivostomatitis and pharyngitis with prodromal fever, myalgia, and cervical lymphadenopathy. The reactivation disease (as seen in this patient) most commonly presents with vesicopustular lesions on the vermilion border with prodromal tingling and burning sensation in the same region. Reactivational HSV-1 infection is rarely associated with systemic symptoms (eg. fever). Although the lesions may also involve the oral mucosa, patients with reactivation disease more commonly present with the involvement of keratinized epithelium with no mucosal involvement. The blisters typically last between 2-21 days before resolving spontaneously. The infection then goes into remission, with recurrence being common and life-long, although the frequency of outbreaks tends to diminish with time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpetigo\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial bacterial skin infection that commonly affects children. It presents with honey-colored crusted lesions or bullae. Impetigo is less likely as this case lacks the crusted appearance, and impetigo is not associated with a prodrome of tingling. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster\u003C/strong\u003E is the reactivation of varicella-zoster and is more common in elderly and/or immunocompromised individuals. Herpes zoster presents as a crop of vesicular lesions along a dermatomal pattern. Oral lesions are unlikely in re-activational herpes zoster.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAphthous stomatitis, \u003C/strong\u003Ealso known as canker sores or mouth ulcers, presents with painful, round, shallow ulcers with a gray-white pseudomembrane and erythematous halo. They occur on non-keratinized mucosa such as the buccal and labial mucosa, soft palate, and ventral tongue. The lack of ulceration and involvement of the vermilion border and skin make aphthous stomatitis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous systemic lupus erythematosus (BSLE) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a rare autoimmune condition that presents with tense bullae involving the sun-exposed skin (ie. photo distribution). Blisters along the vermilion border are typically seen. However, vesicular lesions with primarily localized involvement of vermilion border with no involvement of the rest of the sun-exposed skin make the diagnosis of herpes simplex infection more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactivation of Herpes simplex most commonly presents with vesicopustular lesions around the mouth."],"references":["Crimi S, Fiorillo L, Bianchi A, D\u0027Amico C, Amoroso G, Gorassini F, et al. Herpes Virus, Oral Clinical Signs and QoL: Systematic Review of Recent Data. Viruses. 2019;11(5):463. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31117264/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31819"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15713"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15713"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e9b77887-a893-4feb-9601-d00b0314094c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e9b77887-a893-4feb-9601-d00b0314094c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":582,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31819"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-15T22:04:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-15T22:04:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"